---
description: Sonnet/Haiku fan-out for parallel implementation under one orchestrator
execution_mode: immediate
---

`/team-claude` runs the user's `<prompt>` on a fan-out of Anthropic Sonnet
coding/verifying subagents (with haiku for trivial reads), orchestrated by
this Claude session. Use this for higher-quality work where you want
structured coder+verifier pairs and tighter coordination; pay Sonnet token
cost.

`/team-mini` does the same with MiniMax-M3 — prefer the cheaper one unless
this is a Sonnet-required path.

## Execution steps

1. **Decompose** the user's prompt into 2–6 independent subtasks. Subtasks
   must NOT contend on the same files; each owns its own slice.
2. **Fan out in a single message** — every `Agent` call in one block runs
   concurrently. Pair coder + verifier in the SAME block for independent
   review:

```python
Agent(
    subagent_type="claude-pair-coder",
    isolation="worktree",
    run_in_background=true,
    name="coder-<id>",
    team_name="claude-team-<short-scope>",
    description="<5-10 words>",
    prompt="""..."""
)
Agent(
    subagent_type="claude-pair-verifier",
    isolation="worktree",
    run_in_background=true,
    name="verifier-<id>",
    team_name="claude-team-<short-scope>",
    description="<5-10 words>",
    prompt="""...review the coder's branch..."""
)
```

3. **Haiku** for trivial reads/scans:

```python
Agent(
    subagent_type="general-purpose",
    model="haiku",
    run_in_background=true,
    description="...",
    prompt="""..."""
)
```

4. **Aggregate**. Read the agent outputs as they return, send follow-ups via
   the agent IDs (the system provides a routing channel), and write the
   final summary to the user.

## Subagent types — what each actually does

| Agent type | What it is best at | Cost tier |
|---|---|---|
| `claude-pair-coder` | Implementation, TDD, refactor | Sonnet |
| `claude-pair-verifier` | Adversarial review, test verification | Sonnet |
| `general-purpose` (model="haiku") | File lookups, simple checks | Cheap |
| `general-purpose` (default) | Plain Sonnet fallback | Sonnet |
| `general-purpose` (model="opus") | Hard reasoning, judgement | Expensive — minimize |

## Pair protocol

1. Coder agent implements in a fresh worktree, pushes branch.
2. Verifier agent checks out the coder's branch (its own worktree), runs
   `cargo test` / `npm test` / your preferred verifier, reads the diff
   adversarially, reports defects with file:line.
3. Coder agent fixes defects identified by the verifier (a separate spawn).
4. Verifier agent re-runs on the updated branch.
5. Hand the user the branch URLs.

This is the shape that pairs work in; do not skip the verifier step on
critical changes.

## Failure modes

- Agent never finishes: `/tasks` shows it's running; check the worktree
  `/tmp/wt-<id>` for what it last touched.
- Agent returned but branch is empty: ask the agent for `git log --oneline`
  output in a follow-up.
- Subagents collided on the same files (one overwrote the other): prefer
  better decomposition; not a coder fault.

## Usage

```
/team-claude <prompt>
```

The `<prompt>` is interpreted as a high-level goal; decompose first, then fan
out. No `TeamCreate` / `TaskCreate` / `TaskUpdate` / `SendMessage` exist in
the Claude Code harness exposed to this skill — `Agent` is the primitive.

## Why these docs differ from a generic "Claude team" guide

A lot of Claude-Agent-SDK / `Task` / `TeamCreate` tooling exists in the
broader Anthropic agent ecosystem, but it is **not** what Claude Code's
`Agent` tool exposes in this session. If you find yourself writing
`TeamCreate(...)` or `TaskCreate(...)`, you have copy-pasted from the wrong
reference — there is no TaskList-backed shared task graph here. The
real-time message routing looks similar to `SendMessage`-style agents in
other places; here, the `Agent` tool's `run_in_background: true` +
`isolation: "worktree"` is the equivalent for parallelism + isolation.
